Building a Pok√©mon MVP full stackClaude finished the responseYou said: The primary goal is to deliver a functional MVP that demonstrates understanding of the full stack.The primary goal is to deliver a functional MVP that demonstrates understanding of the full stack. give me some examples with Pokeman09:55оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here's a full-stack Pok√©mon MVP вАФ a working Pok√©dex app that hits the real Pok√©API, with search, stats display, and type filtering.Here's a full-stack Pok√©mon MVP вАФ a working Pok√©dex app that hits the real Pok√©API, with search, stats display, and type filtering. It demonstrates frontend UI, API integration, state management, and data rendering all in one:VConnecting to visualize...Here's what this MVP demonstrates across the full stack:
Data layer вАФ fetches from the real Pok√©API (/pokemon?limit=151) on load, then hydrates each card with type data in parallel using Promise.all.
State management вАФ tracks allPokemon, filtered, currentPage, and selectedId in JS variables, updating only what's needed on each interaction.
API integration вАФ clicking a card fires a second fetch to /api/v2/pokemon/{id} for the detail view (stats, height, weight, official artwork), showing lazy-loading on demand rather than upfront.
UI layer вАФ search filters by name or Pok√©dex number, the type dropdown filters by type (built dynamically from fetched data), and pagination slices the results client-side.
Rendering patterns вАФ the grid uses image-rendering: pixelated for sprites, stat bars are computed as percentages of 255 (the max base stat), and type badge colors are hardcoded as a lookup table вАФ a classic "config object replaces a switch statement" pattern.
This is the kind of architecture you'd pitch as an MVP: one external data source, client-side filtering/pagination, on-demand detail fetching, and zero backend of your own. Click any Pok√©mon to see the stat breakdown!оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: show me websites to use for thisshow me websites to use for this10:00оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here's a quick summary of what each is best for:Searched the webSearched the webVConnecting to visualize...Here's a quick summary of what each is best for:
For the MVP we just built, Pok√©API is your foundation вАФ it provides a RESTful interface to thousands of Pok√©mon objects covering the video game franchise, from moves and abilities to egg groups and evolution chains. It's the one already powering the Pok√©dex above. Pok√©API
The Pok√©API team also maintains wrapper libraries for Node.js, Python, Java/Kotlin, .NET, Swift, PHP, Ruby, Go, TypeScript, and Rust вАФ so whatever stack you're on, there's likely an SDK ready to go. Zuplo
If you want to extend the MVP into trading cards, the Pok√©mon TCG API (now part of Scrydex) is the main developer resource for card and set data in JSON format. And if you need pricing data for a portfolio or valuation tool, PokeTrace aggregates TCGPlayer, eBay, and CardMarket data across markets. Pok√©mon TCGPokeTrace
For the Pok√©dex MVP specifically, the sprite GitHub repo is especially handy вАФ it lets you build image URLs directly like https://raw.githubusercontent.com/PokeAPI/sprites/master/sprites/pokemon/25.png without an extra API call.оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: how would it fit into this Frontend: JavaScript / TypeScripthow would it fit into this Frontend: JavaScript / TypeScriptвЪЩпЄП Backend: Spring BootрЯЧДпЄП Database: MySQL10:02оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here's the full architecture diagram showing how the Pok√©mon MVP slots into your JS/TS + Spring Boot + MySQL stack: Here's how each layer plays its role in theвА¶Here's the full architecture diagram showing how the Pok√©mon MVP slots into your JS/TS + Spring Boot + MySQL stack:VConnecting to visualize...Here's how each layer plays its role in the Pok√©mon MVP:
Frontend (JS/TypeScript) вАФ the React app you saw earlier. The API service layer is a set of typed fetch/Axios wrappers (e.g. pokemonService.ts) that call your Spring Boot endpoints, not Pok√©API directly. State management (useState for simple cases, Zustand for anything shared) holds the current Pok√©mon list, selected Pok√©mon, and filter state.
Backend (Spring Boot) вАФ this is where you move the Pok√©API calls out of the browser. A PokemonController exposes REST endpoints like GET /api/pokemon and GET /api/pokemon/{id}. A PokemonService handles the logic вАФ checking MySQL first, calling Pok√©API via WebClient if the data isn't cached, then saving it. The @Repository layer (Spring Data JPA) handles all SQL through simple interfaces.
Database (MySQL) вАФ three key tables for the MVP: pokemon stores data fetched from Pok√©API so you don't hammer it on every request, favourites adds the user-specific feature that Pok√©API alone can't give you, and api_cache stores raw API responses with a TTL so repeated lookups are instant.
External APIs вАФ Spring Boot calls Pok√©API and the TCG API server-side using WebClient (reactive) or RestTemplate. The frontend never touches these directly, which means you control rate limiting, caching, and error handling centrally rather than relying on every client to behave.
The key architectural win is that your Spring Boot service acts as a proxy + cache layer вАФ the frontend talks only to your API, and MySQL absorbs the repetitive Pok√©API calls. Want me to show the actual Spring Boot controller and service code for this?оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: show me how it would look with jsshow me how it would look with js10:04оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here's the actual JavaScript code for each layer вАФ a walkthrough of how the pieces connect, from the frontend service call all the way to the Spring Boot endpoвА¶Here's the actual JavaScript code for each layer вАФ a walkthrough of how the pieces connect, from the frontend service call all the way to the Spring Boot endpoint and back:VConnecting to visualize...Here's how the request flows through all five files when a user opens the Pok√©dex:

Pokedex component mounts вЖТ useEffect fires вЖТ calls getPokemonList(0) in pokemonService.js
pokemonService.js hits GET /api/pokemon?page=0&size=20 on your Spring Boot server
PokemonController receives it, calls service.getPage(PageRequest.of(0, 20))
PokemonService calls repo.findAll(pageable) вАФ Spring Data generates the SQL automatically
If the table is empty (first run), getById triggers fetchAndSave, which calls Pok√©API via WebClient, saves to MySQL, then returns the DTO
The JSON response flows back through the controller вЖТ fetch вЖТ setPokemon(data.content) вЖТ React re-renders the grid

The key pattern to notice in PokemonService is the cache-first check вАФ repo.findById(id).orElseGet(() -> fetchAndSave(id)). This means Pok√©API only gets called once per Pok√©mon, ever. After that it's a straight MySQL read. Want me to show the application.properties config for the MySQL connection, or the DTO/mapper classes next?оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: just show the simple version what is needed for sqljust show the simple version what is needed for sql10:06оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here's the MySQL schema you need:Here's the MySQL schema you need:
sqlCREATE DATABASE pokedex;
USE pokedex;

CREATE TABLE pokemon (
  id          INT PRIMARY KEY,
  name        VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
  types       VARCHAR(100),
  sprite_url  VARCHAR(255),
  base_hp     INT,
  base_attack INT,
  base_defense INT,
  base_speed  INT
);

CREATE TABLE favourites (
  id         BIGINT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
  user_id    VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
  pokemon_id INT NOT NULL,
  saved_at   TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
  FOREIGN KEY (pokemon_id) REFERENCES pokemon(id)
);
And in application.properties:
propertiesspring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/pokedex
spring.datasource.username=root
spring.datasource.password=yourpassword
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update
spring.jpa.show-sql=true
That's it. The ddl-auto=update means Spring Boot will create the tables automatically from your entity classes if you'd rather skip writing the SQL вАФ but the schema above is the manual equivalent. The pokemon table acts as your cache, and favourites is the only table that stores anything user-specific.оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: show me a good site how to connect front end to backendshow me a good site how to connect front end to backend10:13оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here are the best resources, matched to where you are in the build:Searched the webSearched the webHere are the best resources, matched to where you are in the build:
