js// src/services/pokemonService.js

const BASE_URL = 'http://localhost:8080/api';

export async function getPokemonList(page = 0, size = 20) {
  const res = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}/pokemon?page=${page}&size=${size}`);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return res.json();
}

export async function getPokemonById(id) {
  const res = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}/pokemon/${id}`);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return res.json();
}

export async function searchPokemon(query) {
  const res = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}/pokemon/search?name=${encodeURIComponent(query)}`);
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return res.json();
}

export async function saveFavourite(userId, pokemonId) {
  const res = await fetch(`${BASE_URL}/favourites`, {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ userId, pokemonId }),
  });
  if (!res.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${res.status}`);
  return res.json();
}
Then call it from any plain JS file or component:
js// index.js or wherever you need it

import { getPokemonList, getPokemonById } from './services/pokemonService.js';

// Load first page
getPokemonList(0, 20)
  .then(data => console.log(data.content))
  .catch(err => console.error(err));

// Load a single Pok√©mon
getPokemonById(25)
  .then(p => console.log(p.name)) // "pikachu"
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
And make sure your Spring Boot controller allows the request with CORS:
java@CrossOrigin(origins = "http://localhost:5173") // or :3000 if not using Vite
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/pokemon")
public class PokemonController { ... }
That's the whole connection вАФ fetch on the JS side, @CrossOrigin on the Java side. No Axios, no extra libraries needed.оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: show me websitesshow me websites10:17оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here are the best sites, ordered by what to read first:Searched the webSearched the webHere are the best sites, ordered by what to read first:
1. MDN Web Docs вАФ the official reference
MDN covers the Fetch API as the main tool for making HTTP requests from JavaScript to a server, with real-world examples of how to retrieve JSON and update the page without a full reload.
рЯСЙ developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/JavaScript/Client-side_web_APIs/Fetching_data MDN Web Docs
2. W3Schools вАФ quickest syntax lookup
W3Schools has a dedicated JavaScript Fetch API page with simple, runnable examples вАФ good for quickly checking syntax when you forget the exact structure of a fetch() call.
рЯСЙ w3schools.com/js/js_api_fetch.asp W3Schools
3. since1979.dev вАФ async/await + error handling
This guide goes beyond basics вАФ it covers using async/await for cleaner code, proper HTTP error handling, and important headers like Content-Type: application/json that your Spring Boot backend expects on POST requests.
рЯСЙ since1979.dev/modern-javascript-fetch-api-guide-to-async-await-error-handling Since1979
4. ELITEX вАФ understanding the frontend/backend connection
ELITEX explains the five ways to connect frontend and backend (REST, GraphQL, WebSockets, SSR, gRPC) and walks through a practical example of fetching data and displaying it вАФ useful context for understanding why REST with fetch() is the right choice for your MVP.
рЯСЙ elitex.systems/blog/how-to-connect-frontend-and-backend-all-you-need-to-know-in ELITEX
5. GeeksforGeeks вАФ CRUD operations with fetch
GeeksforGeeks shows how to use fetch() to perform full CRUD (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) against a REST API using JSONPlaceholder as a practice backend вАФ perfect for testing your service functions before Spring Boot is fully wired up.
рЯСЙ geeksforgeeks.org/blogs/how-to-connect-front-end-and-backend GeeksforGeeks
Start with MDN for understanding, W3Schools for syntax, and GeeksforGeeks for hands-on CRUD practice.оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: for beginnersfor beginners10:18оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Here are the best beginner-friendly sites for learning how to connect JavaScript to a backend: The recommended order for a beginner:Here are the best beginner-friendly sites for learning how to connect JavaScript to a backend:Searched the webSearched the webVConnecting to visualize...The recommended order for a beginner:
Start with W3Schools to get a feel for the syntax, then read the MDN guide to understand why it works. Before touching Spring Boot at all, practice your fetch() calls against JSONPlaceholder вАФ it's a free dummy REST API that lets you make real GET, POST, PUT, and DELETE requests with no server setup needed. Once that clicks, connecting to your own Spring Boot backend will feel straightforward because it behaves the same way. GeeksforGeeks
A weather app is the classic beginner project for practising fetch and async/await вАФ it uses the same pattern as your Pok√©mon service: call an external API, get JSON back, display it on the page. Building one first is great preparation before wiring up the full Spring Boot stack. ScrimbaоБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: it would be a concept where the users can create thier own characterit would be a concept where the users can create thier own character10:20оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: That's a great concept вАФ a character creator where users build a custom Pok√©mon-style character and save it.That's a great concept вАФ a character creator where users build a custom Pok√©mon-style character and save it. Here's how it would look and feel:VConnecting to visualize...Here's how this maps to your full stack:
Frontend (JS) вАФ the creator UI collects name, colour, types, ability, and stats into a plain object. The "Save character" button would call fetch('http://localhost:8080/api/characters', { method: 'POST', body: JSON.stringify(character) }) to persist it.
Backend (Spring Boot) вАФ a CharacterController with POST /api/characters to save and GET /api/characters to list all saved characters. The service layer validates that no more than 2 types are selected before saving.
