VvisualizeVvisualize show_widgetHere's what's happening at each step:
1. User fills the form вАФ name, class, stats
2. Select class вЖТ stats autofill instantly via form.js (no API call yet, just JS)
3. Click Generate вЖТ JS builds this JSON and sends it to Spring Boot:
json{
  "name": "Kael",
  "charClass": "Warrior",
  "strength": 80,
  "agility": 50,
  "intelligence": 25
}
4. Spring Boot receives it вЖТ saves to MySQL вЖТ sends back:
json{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "Kael",
  "charClass": "Warrior",
  "strength": 80
}
5. JS gets the response вЖТ reveals the card
The log box at the bottom shows you exactly what gets sent and what comes back вАФ useful for seeing the data flow while you're building. Once your Spring Boot server is running on localhost:8080 the fetch call will connect live.оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: user table - user creates a character and then connect character to user through user id - tell me how in notesuser table - user creates a character and then connect character to user through user id - tell me how in notes11:14оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: User вЖТ Character ConnectionUser вЖТ Character Connection

The Idea

A user registers and logs in
They create a character
That character is linked to them through their user ID
Every character knows which user it belongs to


The Tables
users
- id          (Primary Key, auto generated)
- username
- email
- password

characters
- id          (Primary Key, auto generated)
- user_id     (Foreign Key вЖТ links to users.id)
- name
- class
- strength
- agility
- intelligence

The Link

user_id in the characters table is the connection
When a character is created it stores the logged in users ID
That one column is what connects the two tables


The Relationship

One user вЖТ many characters
Each character belongs to one user only


The Order Of Events

User registers вЖТ a row is created in the users table
User logs in вЖТ their user_id is returned
User fills in the form and clicks Generate
The user_id is sent along with the character data
Character is saved in the characters table with the user_id attached
Character card reveals


What Gets Sent To The API
json{
  "userId": 1,
  "name": "Kael",
  "charClass": "Warrior",
  "strength": 80,
  "agility": 50,
  "intelligence": 25
}

What Spring Boot Does

Receives the character data including the userId
Checks the user exists in the users table
Saves the character with the user_id attached
Returns the saved character back to the frontend


What MySQL Stores
users table
id | username | email
1  | Kael     | kael@email.com

characters table
id | user_id | name | class   | strength
1  | 1       | Kael | Warrior | 80
2  | 1       | Zara | Mage    | 25

Both characters belong to user ID 1
One user, two characters


In Spring Boot
java// Find all characters for a user
List<Character> findByUserId(Long userId);

In JS
js// Send user_id with the character when saving
const payload = {
  userId: 1,
  name: "Kael",
  charClass: "Warrior",
  strength: 80
}

Simple Rule

No user_id = character belongs to nobody
With user_id = character is locked to that user forever
оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: what is DNDwhat is DND11:30оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: D&D вАФ Dungeons & DragonsD&D вАФ Dungeons & Dragons

What It Is

A tabletop role-playing game (RPG)
Players create characters and go on adventures together
One person is the Dungeon Master (DM) вАФ they control the story and the world
Everyone else plays as their own character


How It Works

You create a character with a class (Warrior, Mage, Rogue etc)
You roll dice to determine your stats (strength, agility, intelligence)
The DM describes a scenario
You decide what your character does
You roll dice to see if it works


The Classes

Warrior вАФ fights in melee combat
Mage вАФ casts spells
Rogue вАФ sneaks and steals
Paladin вАФ holy warrior
Ranger вАФ archer and tracker
Bard вАФ storyteller and charmer
Druid вАФ controls nature
Monk вАФ martial arts fighter


The Dice

D4, D6, D8, D10, D12, D20
D20 is the most important вАФ roll high to succeed
Roll a 20 = critical success
Roll a 1 = critical fail


Why It's Relevant To Your Project

Your character creator is very similar to D&D character creation
Class вЖТ auto stats is a core D&D mechanic
Elements, bio, artwork вАФ all straight from D&D
Your app is essentially a digital D&D character card generator


The Connection To Your App
D&DYour AppCharacter sheetCharacter cardClass selectionClass dropdownStat rollingAuto stat fillDungeon MasterSpring Boot (generates the data)PlayerThe user

In Short

D&D is the inspiration behind almost everything in your character creator app
Class, stats, elements, bio вАФ all D&D concepts
Your app is a digital version of filling out a D&D character sheet
оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: how do different people create branches from one repo?how do different people create branches from one repo?11:30оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Git Branching вАФ How Multiple People Work From One RepoGit Branching вАФ How Multiple People Work From One Repo

The Idea

Everyone works from the same repo
Each person creates their own branch
They work on their branch without affecting anyone else
When done they merge their branch back into main


The Setup

One person creates the repo and pushes it to GitHub
Everyone else clones it to their machine
Each person creates their own branch to work on


The Commands
Clone the repo (first time only)
bashgit clone https://github.com/yourrepo/characterapp.git
Create your own branch
bashgit checkout -b feature/character-form
Check which branch you are on
bashgit branch
Make changes, then save them
bashgit add .
git commit -m "added character form"
Push your branch to GitHub
bashgit push origin feature/character-form
Merge back into main when done
bashgit checkout main
git merge feature/character-form

How A Team Would Split The Work
PersonBranchPerson 1feature/character-formPerson 2feature/spring-boot-apiPerson 3feature/database-setupPerson 4feature/character-card

Everyone works at the same time
Nobody blocks anyone else
All branches come from main
All branches merge back into main when done


The Flow
main
 вФЬвФАвФА feature/character-form      вЖР Person 1
 вФЬвФАвФА feature/spring-boot-api     вЖР Person 2
 вФЬвФАвФА feature/database-setup      вЖР Person 3
 вФФвФАвФА feature/character-card      вЖР Person 4

Pull Requests

When your branch is done you open a Pull Request on GitHub
The team reviews your code
If it looks good it gets merged into main
Everyone then pulls the latest main to stay up to date

Pull the latest main
bashgit checkout main
git pull origin main

Golden Rules

Never work directly on main
Always create a branch for new work
Pull from main regularly so you stay up to date
Commit often with clear messages
One feature per branch вАФ keep it focused
оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: how can you do it on githubhow can you do it on github11:41оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Creating & Managing Branches on GitHub (No Terminal)Creating & Managing Branches on GitHub (No Terminal)

Create a Branch on GitHub

Go to your repo on GitHub
Click the branch dropdown (says main)
Type your new branch name
Click Create branch: feature/character-form
Branch is created вАФ you are now on it


Make Changes On GitHub

Navigate to the file you want to edit
Click the pencil icon (top right of the file)
Make your changes
Scroll down to Commit changes
Write a message e.g. added character form
Select Commit directly to feature/character-form
Click Commit changes


Open a Pull Request

Go to the Pull requests tab
Click New pull request
Set base to main and compare to your branch
Click Create pull request
Add a title and description
Click Submit pull request


Merge Into Main

Open the pull request
Team reviews the code
Click Merge pull request
Click Confirm merge
Branch is merged into main


Delete The Branch After Merge

After merging click Delete branch
Keeps the repo clean


Switch Between Branches

Click the branch dropdown on the repo home page
Click the branch you want to switch to
All files update to show that branch


See All Branches

Click the branch dropdown
Click View all branches
See who is working on what


The Flow On GitHub
1. Create branch on GitHub
       вЖУ
2. Edit files in the browser
       вЖУ
3. Commit changes to your branch
       вЖУ
4. Open a Pull Request
       вЖУ
5. Team reviews
       вЖУ
6. Merge into main
       вЖУ
7. Delete branch

Golden Rules

Never commit directly to main
One branch per feature
Always write a clear commit message
Review before merging
Delete branch after merge to keep things tidy
