Example вАФ CharacterService.java
javapackage com.dndproject.service;

// imports go here at the top
import com.dndproject.model.Character;
import com.dndproject.model.CharacterClass;
import com.dndproject.model.Element;
import com.dndproject.model.Stat;
import com.dndproject.repository.CharacterRepository;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import java.util.List;

@Service
public class CharacterService {

    private final CharacterRepository repo;

    public CharacterService(CharacterRepository repo) {
        this.repo = repo;
    }

    public List<Character> getAll(Long userId) {
        return repo.findByUserId(userId);
    }

    public Character create(Character character) {
        return repo.save(character);
    }
}

The Rule

package always goes on line 1
imports always go after the package
Your class code goes after the imports
IntelliJ will actually do this automatically вАФ start typing the class name and press Enter when it suggests it


IntelliJ Shortcut

If you forget to import just hover over the red underlined word
Click Import class
IntelliJ adds it for you automatically

You only need to import a model in files that use it вАФ so CharacterService.java, CharacterController.java and CharacterRepository.javaоБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОpackage com.example.Create_Character.model;

