What you saw in Character.java
java@OneToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
@JoinColumn(name = "element_id")
private Element element;

@OneToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
@JoinColumn(name = "class_id")
private CharacterClass characterClassName;

@OneToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
@JoinColumn(name = "stats_id")
private Stat stat;

What this means

@JoinColumn(name = "element_id") = this IS the foreign key
Instead of storing just the ID number it stores the whole Element object
Spring Boot handles the foreign key relationship automatically
In MySQL it will create element_id, class_id, stats_id columns automatically


So your foreign keys are:
Column in MySQLLinks toelement_idelement tableclass_idclass tablestats_idstats tableuser_idusers table

Simple answer вАФ the foreign keys are already in the model using @JoinColumn. You do not need to add them manually вАФ Spring Boot creates them in MySQL automatically when the app runs.оБЦоАїоГїоГєоГОYou said: wait if i put the getter and setter myself what if Bradley does it?wait if i put the getter and setter myself what if Bradley does it?10:01оГОоБ§оБЦоАїClaude responded: Good catch вАФ this is a potential conflict.Good catch вАФ this is a potential conflict.

